MOTION to Dismiss filed by Mark W. Vargo, Breht T. Feigh, American Dental Partners, Inc., Gregory A. Serrano. After hearing, the motion to dismiss is DENIED by the court in an oral ruling. The court notes that the PSLRA does not alter the standard to be applied on a motion to dismiss; while a plaintiff must show a strong inference of scienter, all inferences are nonetheless drawn in plaintiff's favor. Aldridge v. A.T. Cross Corp., 284 F.3d 72, 78 (1st Cir. 2002). The court finds that as pled, defendants' public disclosures of ongoing litigation were not predictions, but were misrepresentations concealing adverse facts then known to defendants. In re Credit Suisse First Boston Corp., 431 F.3d 36, 47 (1st Cir. 2005). The court further notes the impact of Tellabs, Inc. v. Makor Issues & Rights, Ltd., 551 U.S. 308 (2007), on the import of equally compelling inferences. The court finds all other elements of a Section 10(b) and Rule 10b-5 action to be adequately pled. Dura Pharm., Inc. v. Broudo, 544 U.S. 336 (2005). Finally, the court notes that scienter need not be pled under the rigorous standards of the PSLRA to state a claim under Section 20(a). In re Stone & Webster, Inc. Sec. Litig., 414 F.3d 187, 194 (1st Cir. 2005). The parties shall file a joint proposed discovery order within 20 days of today's date. SO ORDERED. (Court Reporter: J. Gibbons.)(Attorneys present: Ta, McIntyre (for plaintiff); Donovan, Ropple (for defendants)) (RGS, law2) (Entered: 04/02/2009) Docket Item 35 | United States Courts Archive











You're viewing Docket Item 35 from the case MOTION to Dismiss filed by Mark W. Vargo, Breht T. Feigh, American Dental Partners, Inc., Gregory A. Serrano. After hearing, the motion to dismiss is DENIED by the court in an oral ruling. The court notes that the PSLRA does not alter the standard to be applied on a motion to dismiss; while a plaintiff must show a strong inference of scienter, all inferences are nonetheless drawn in plaintiff's favor. Aldridge v. A.T. Cross Corp., 284 F.3d 72, 78 (1st Cir. 2002). The court finds that as pled, defendants' public disclosures of ongoing litigation were not predictions, but were misrepresentations concealing adverse facts then known to defendants. In re Credit Suisse First Boston Corp., 431 F.3d 36, 47 (1st Cir. 2005). The court further notes the impact of Tellabs, Inc. v. Makor Issues & Rights, Ltd., 551 U.S. 308 (2007), on the import of equally compelling inferences. The court finds all other elements of a Section 10(b) and Rule 10b-5 action to be adequately pled. Dura Pharm., Inc. v. Broudo, 544 U.S. 336 (2005). Finally, the court notes that scienter need not be pled under the rigorous standards of the PSLRA to state a claim under Section 20(a). In re Stone & Webster, Inc. Sec. Litig., 414 F.3d 187, 194 (1st Cir. 2005). The parties shall file a joint proposed discovery order within 20 days of today's date. SO ORDERED. (Court Reporter: J. Gibbons.)(Attorneys present: Ta, McIntyre (for plaintiff); Donovan, Ropple (for defendants)) (RGS, law2) (Entered: 04/02/2009). View the full docket and case details.
